        <div class="tab-row scaffold">────────────</div>
        <div class="tab-row"><span class="value">      216488</span>   <span class="scaffold">←</span> 54122 × <span class="value">4</span></div>
        <div class="tab-row"><span class="value">    43297600</span>   <span class="scaffold">←</span> 54122 × <span class="value">800</span></div>
        <div class="tab-row"><span class="value">   432976000</span>   <span class="scaffold">←</span> 54122 × <span class="value">8000</span></div>
        <div class="tab-row"><span class="value">  1623660000</span>   <span class="scaffold">←</span> 54122 × <span class="value">30000</span></div>
        <div class="tab-row scaffold">────────────</div>
        <div class="tab-row"><span class="value">  2100150088</span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="dual-caption">
        <div class="dual-item">
          <span class="dual-swatch scaffold-swatch"></span>
          <span class="dual-key">Shape</span>
          <span class="dual-val">align, multiply, shift, sum — the learned procedure.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="dual-item">
          <span class="dual-swatch value-swatch"></span>
          <span class="dual-key">Operations</span>
          <span class="dual-val">partial products and the final addition — learned facts.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="dual-note">Both are recall. Both contribute steps to <em>p<sub>step</sub><sup>N</sup></em>.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Prose>
    <p>
      The setup works while the problem stays close to what the model has seen.
      When the exact instance is new, the learned procedure reduces it to smaller
      pieces the model does know. A 12-digit multiplication becomes roughly 144
      single-digit products, plus carries and alignment. Each piece is familiar,
      but the chain is now long enough that one miss can spoil the run.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">How the chain collapses</h3>
    <p>
      Increase one variable — operand size — and the rest follows: more steps,
      lower per-step accuracy, lower end-to-end reliability.
    </p>
  </Prose>

  <div class="panels">
    {#if data}
      {#each PICK as { digit, probe, label } (digit + ':' + probe)}
        {@const trace = pick(data.traces, digit, probe)}
        {#if trace}
          {@const predicted = Math.pow(trace.pStep, trace.totalSteps)}
          <div class="panel">
            <div class="panel-header">
              <div class="size">{digit}-digit × {digit}-digit</div>
              <div class="regime">{label}</div>
            </div>
            <div class="problem">
              <div class="operands">
                <span>{formatNumberWithCommas(trace.operands.a)}</span>
                <span class="times">×</span>
                <span>{formatNumberWithCommas(trace.operands.b)}</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid" aria-label={`${trace.totalSteps} partial products, ${trace.correctSteps} correct`}>
              {#each trace.partialProducts as pp, i (i)}
                <span class="dot" class:ok={pp.correct} class:err={!pp.correct}
                      title={`${pp.expr} = ${pp.stated}${pp.correct ? ' ✓' : ` ✗ (actual ${pp.actual})`}`}></span>
              {/each}
            </div>
            <div class="stats">
              <div class="stat">
                <span class="k">N</span>
                <span class="v">{trace.totalSteps}</span>
                <span class="d">observed steps</span>
              </div>
              <div class="stat">
                <span class="k">p<sub>step</sub></span>
                <span class="v">{trace.pStep.toFixed(3)}</span>
                <span class="d">{trace.correctSteps} / {trace.totalSteps} correct</span>
              </div>
              <div class="stat">
                <span class="k">p<sub>step</sub><sup>N</sup></span>
                <span class="v">{scientific(predicted)}</span>
                <span class="d">predicted success</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="outcome" class:ok={trace.finalCorrect} class:err={!trace.finalCorrect}>
              {#if trace.finalCorrect}
                ✓ Haiku answered correctly
              {:else}
                ✗ Haiku answered incorrectly
              {/if}
            </div>
          </div>
        {/if}
      {/each}
    {/if}
  </div>

  <Prose>
    <p>
      The hard case did not require a new algorithm. It required the same learned
      operation to fire cleanly many more times. Eventually one step missed, and
      the remaining chain inherited the damage.
    </p>
  </Prose>
</section>

